# Roadmap

Run-local milestones for one planned roadmap run. Each `M-N` is one planned
chunk of work. Flow ticks `[x]` automatically when `flow close` finalizes a
child change in the same run whose `status.md` references the milestone.
If this roadmap was generated from a specific assignment, `/flow-roadmap` may
write the H1 as `# Roadmap: <Descriptor>`; `flow run` uses that descriptor
for run directories, run logs, manuals, and run branches.

> **Editing rules.** This file is yours to edit within the run. Add, reorder,
> and rephrase milestones freely, then run `flow run --rescan` before
> continuing. Flow only ever flips a linked milestone to `[x]` during close; it
> preserves milestone body text exactly.

## How it works

1. Add a milestone. `/flow-roadmap` emits the source-preserving five-field
   heading shape:

   ```markdown
   ### [ ] M-N: Short outcome title

   Source: `<source file or prompt>`, sections <section numbers/headings>.

   Outcome: <one or two sentences describing delivered user value>.

   Must preserve:
   - <specific requirement, constraint, copy string, or behavior>

   Done when:
   - <observable acceptance outcome>
   - <test or verification evidence expected>

   Do not include:
   - <explicit non-goal or deferred item>
   ```

   Short milestones may use the same heading plus a single descriptive
   paragraph.

2. Start a change linked to an existing milestone:
   `FLOW_RUN_DIR=<run-dir> /flow-start M-N`. Flow creates a child change under
   `flow/runs/<run>/changes/<change>/`, leaves this roadmap unchanged, and
   records `**Milestone**: M-N` in `status.md`.

3. Close the change with `/flow-close`. Flow flips the checkbox to `[x]`,
   verifies central documentation evidence, stamps the change closed in place,
   and updates `run.md` without creating tags. Standalone closeout does not
   create commits.

